tecture of Oblivion examines the role of ruins in the development of Russia's historical consciousness from the eighteenth century to the present. Investigating the meaning and functions ruins have acquired in Russian culture, Schönle looks at ideological reasons for the current disregard for the value of ruins and historical buildings, in particular by political authorities, and reveals how ruins have often become a site of resistance to official ideology and an invitation to map out alternative visions of history and of statehood. An interdisciplinary study of Russia's response to ruins has never been attempted, although the topic of ruins has garnered considerable interest in Western Europe and in the U.S. This original work from a leading authority on the subject will appeal to historians of Russian culture and thought, literature and art scholars, and general readers interested in ruins.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArchitecture and societyzRussiaxHistory. 0aArchitecture and societyzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aArchitecturezRussiaxAestheticsxHistory. 0aArchitecturezSoviet UnionxAestheticsxHistory. 0aCity and town lifezRussiaxHistory. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussian ruins, post-Soviet Russian destruction and reconstruction, Russia's historical consciousness, Russian disregard for ruins and historical buildings.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175677140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501756771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501756771/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HIC